snippet.textDisplay:
We have very high taxes in Finland (income, VAT, cars, sugar in food and drink and so on) but at least here everything works automatically. Income tax is automatically charged every time you get your salary. VAT and other taxes are included in the price of whatever you're buying. All you need to do is tell the government an estimate of how much you're going to make this year. If you make less than your estimate, they'll refund the extra tax you've paid (the more money you make, the higher your tax percentage). And if you make more than you estimated, they'll send you an invoice for the amount of taxes you need to pay with some penalty sum added. Basically you always just overestimate your yearly income, pay a bit more than you would have needed to pay and the next year you'll get a nice bonus money payment from the government for the extra you paid last year.
The American tax system is just ridiculous.
